If you take a look at your interface, you&#39;ll notice that `e` property is actually defined as array.

    e:{
        aa:number;
        cc:{
          aaa:string;
        }
    }[] // NOTICE THIS!

That&#39;s the reason you need to use indexer `[0]` to get the type of item of that array. It&#39;s not a hack, actually it&#39;s added in typescript since 2.1 and the official name is [indexed access types, also called lookup types][1].


  [1]: https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/wiki/What&#39;s-new-in-TypeScript#keyof-and-lookup-types

